Carbon footprint
means the sum of greenhouse gas emissions and greenhouse gas remo
vals in a product system,
expressed as CO equivalents and based on a life cycle assessment using the single impact category
of climate change. (ESPR Art 2 25))

Circular Economy indicators are measures for relevant monitoring the transition to a circular economy and to measure the effects of new policy and trends.

See also https://environment.ec.europa.eu/strategy/circular-economy-action-plan_en
A classification code from some product classification scheme .

Concentration of the substance of concern
the concentration of the substances of concern, at the level of the product, its relevant components,
or spare parts ESPR Art 7(5)

The product passport should be defined at the level of item, batch or product model, depending on specific needs and complexity of the value chain, the size, nature or impacts of the products considered. (Standardisation Request 5423 7)

Digital instructions
mean instructions in digital format concerning the product (‘digital instructions’) in a language that
can be easily understood. ESPR Art 27(7)
Digital instructions are ensured by manufacturers. These should a
lso ensured by importers. (ESPR
Art 29(4))

Disposal instructions of the product.

Durability
means the ability
of a product to maintain over time its function and performance under specified
conditions of use, maintenance and repair. (ESPR Art 2 (22))

Digita Product Passport (DPP)
means a set of data specific to a product that includes the information specified in the app
licable
delegated act adopted pursuant to Article 4 and that is accessible via electronic means through a
data carrier in accordance with Chapter III. (ESPR Art 2 (28))

Emission is the act or amount of sending out gas, heat, light, etc. It can also refer to harmful substances that are released into the environment, especially carbon dioxide.

https://dictionary.cambridge.org/dictionary/english/emission

Environmental footprint
means a quantification of the environmental impacts resulting from a product throughout its life
cycle, whether in relation to a single environmental impact category or an aggregated set of impact
categories based on the Product Environmental Footprint method established by Recommendation
(EU) 2 021/2279 or other scientific methods developed by int ernational organisations, widely tested
in collaboration with different industry sectors and adopted or implemented by the Commission in
other Union law. (ESPR Art 2 (24)).

Product parameters list ESPR Annex I
(m) The environmental footprint of the product, expressed as a quantification;

Environmental pollution is the addition of any substance or form of energy to the environment at a rate faster than it can be dispersed or safely stored.

https://www.britannica.com/science/pollution-environment

A Facility may be a place where specific activities occur.

A production/manufacturing facility means a factory. The term may refer to any place that makes things, or plants that generate electricity.

https://marketbusinessnews.com/financial-glossary/facility/

Business facilities are structures that provide services to a business. This can include space for employees, technology, equipment and inventory. Facilities can be used for business administration, operations or to provide services to customers.

Material footprint
refers to the total amount of raw materials extracted to meet final consumpt
ion demands. (ESPR
Art 2 (26))

A property (respectively measurand of a property) of the product (model) that is expressed by a quantity value. A specific quantity. (VIM 2.3: The specification of a measurand requires knowledge of the kind of quantity, description of the state of the phenomenon, body, or substance carrying the quantity, including any relevant component, and the chemical entities involved.)

Recycling instructions of the product.
Instructions for the refurbishment of the product.

Reliability
 is the ability of an item to perform its function under specified conditions over a given period.
 It is usually expressed in terms of mean time between failures (MTBF), which is the average length of time that a device will operate without failure.

Reliability
means the probability that a product functions as required under given conditions for a given
duration without an occurrence which results in a primary or secondary function of the product no
longer being performed. (ESPR Art 2 (16))
Repair instructions. (ESPR Annex I (b))

service. (ESPR Art 2 (49))

By default, information on all substances of concern present in a product, above the  relevant thresholds, should be included in the DPP [ESPR FAQ 10.115, p59]
